<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-239-472  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 239 472.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  March 12 1990 v24 n11 p39(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Weeding out virus makers. (Small Talk) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Barney, Douglas.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer viruses such as Byte Warrior continue to pose problemsfor information systems managers (IS) and anyone else whose systembecomes infected with one.andP;  Many viruses are fairly innocuous andcan be quickly recognized by virus detective programs and zappedby other anti-viral programs, but the sense of violation remains.andO;The term computer hacker once rather gloriously referred tosomeone truly expert and ingenious in their understanding ofcomputer systems and what made them work.andP;  Thanks to the trial andsubsequent conviction of Robert Morris, computer hacker has becomea term worthy of fear and disdain.andP;  Morris was simply showing offhis talents, but he chose the wrong vehicle.andP;  Reports show thatMorris' viruses did not destroy data, it just added a lot of extragarbage to infected workstations.andP;  IS managers have learned topractice greater caution and employ security measures to protectdata and systems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer virusesCourt CasesComputer CrimesComputer HackersFraud.andO;Person:    Morris, Robert T., Jr. (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>